<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="56" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,151,364]" box="[151,647,151,177]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,647,151,177]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="15" pageNumber="56" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,647,151,177]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">
<taxonomicName authority="Piza, 1950" authorityName="Piza" authorityYear="1950" box="[151,528,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Euceraia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufithorax" status="stat. nov.">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,394,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">Euceraia rufithorax</emphasis>
Piza, 
<number box="[470,528,151,177]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56" value="1950.0">1950</number>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[536,647,151,177]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">stat. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,151,364]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">
This species has been synonymized by 
<bibRefCitation author="Grant" box="[689,845,189,215]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56" refString="Grant Jr., H. J. (1964) A revision of the genera Ceraia and Euceraia with notes on their relationship to Scudderia. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences, Philadelphia, 116, 29 - 117." type="journal article" year="1964">
Grant (
<number box="[776,837,189,215]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56" value="1964.0">1964</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
under 
<taxonomicName authority="Chopard, 1918" authorityName="Chopard" authorityYear="1918" box="[937,1432,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Euceraia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufovariegata">
<emphasis box="[937,1217,189,214]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">Euceraia rufovariegata</emphasis>
(Chopard, 
<number box="[1360,1423,189,215]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56" value="1918.0">1918</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
. According to Grant, who relied on Piza’s description and sketchy illustration of the male abdomen tip, there are two morphologically different populations, whose conspicuous coloration, however, is uniform. The male 
<typeStatus box="[151,244,301,327]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">neotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[284,480,301,326]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Euceraia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufovariegata">
<emphasis box="[284,480,301,326]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">E. rufovariegata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the male 
<typeStatus box="[648,751,301,327]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[791,944,301,326]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Euceraia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufithorax">
<emphasis box="[791,944,301,326]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">E. rufithorax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are very different in coloration, the latter lacking the prominent dark red markings completely.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
